ABSTRACT
Introduction: : Pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH) is a rare pulmonary vasculopathy. This review
focuses on selexipag, a prostacyclin receptor agonist validated for the treatment of PAH.
Areas covered: We review the structure, mechanisms of action, pharmacokinetics, and pharmacody-
namics of selexipag. Clinical efficacy and tolerability are discussed using the main clinical trial published
for selexipag (GRIPHON) and its post-hoc analysis.
Expert opinion: Selexipag should be added as a triple oral combination therapy in case of insufficient
response to oral combination therapy with endothelin receptor antagonist and phosphodiesterase 5
inhibitor. However, selexipag should not replace parenteral prostacyclin in high-risk patients.

1. Introduction on PAH and treatments
Pulmonary arterial hypertension (group 1) (PAH) is a rare,
incurable pulmonary vasculopathy progressively leading to
right heart failure and eventually death. It is diagnosed after
exclusion of other causes of pulmonary hypertension (PH)
(groups 2, 3, 4, and 5) according to current guidelines and
confirmed by right heart catheterization (RHC) showing
a precapillary PH (mean pulmonary arterial pressure (mPAP)
of 25 mmHg and pulmonary arterial wedge pressure (PAWP)
15 mmHg) [1]. Of interest, this definition has been recently
challenged during the world symposium on PH and a new
definition including mPAP > 20 mmHg, PAWP 15 mmHg,
and pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR) 3 WU is suggested
[2]. PAH can be classified according to its etiology: 1.1 idio-
pathic PAH (IPAH), 1.2 heritable PAH (HPAH) (BMPR2 and other
genetic mutations), 1.3 drug- and toxin-induced PAH (DPAH),
1.4.1 PAH associated with connective tissue disease (CTD)
(especially systemic sclerosis but also systemic lupus erythe-
matous and rarely others CTD), 1.4.2 human immunodefi-
ciency virus (HIV), 1.4.3 portal hypertension (PoPH), 1.4.4
congenital heart disease (CHD), and 1.4.5 schistosomiasis [2].
PAH can be further stratified according to the part of the
vasculature mainly damaged: 1) PAH when the arteries (medium
and small) are involved and 2) pulmonary veno-occlusive disease
(PVOD) and pulmonary capillary hemangiomatosis (PCH) when
the venules, respectively, the capillaries, are damaged. While
PVOD and PCH were formerly in a subgroup of PAH (group 1),
the proceedings of the 6
th
World symposium on PH suggested to
unify these entities in a group 1.6 called PAH with overt features of
venous/capillaries (PVOD/PCH) involvement [2]. This decision was
based on the growing acknowledgment that overlaps between
arteries, capillaries, and venules involvements are important. PAH,
PCH, and PVOD are then a spectrum of diseases rather than strictly
different entities. However, differentiation between PAH with or
without overt features of PVOD/PCH is mandatory because the
therapeutic approach significantly differs. In fact, no randomized
controlled trial (RCT) included patients with PCH/PVOD features.
When PCH/PVOD is suspected, classical vasodilator therapies
should be used under close supervision in an expert center due
to the risk of pulmonary edema [1,3]. Early transplantation listing is
a priority for these patients with a poor prognosis. PVOD/PCH is
suspected based on CT findings (septal lines, mediastinal lymph
node enlargement, and centrilobular ground glass opacities), low
DLCO, poor response to PAH therapy, specific genetic back-
ground, and eventually occult alveolar hemorrhage when bronch-
oalveolar lavage is performed [2].
PAH long-term responders to calcium channel blockers
(group 1.5) are one other special population because of spe-
cific treatment and better prognosis [2]. In patients with sus-
pected IPAH, DPAH, and HPAH, a pulmonary vasoreactivity
testing is performed, generally using inhaled nitric oxide
(NO), after PAH diagnosis confirmation by RHC [2]. The test is
positive when there is a reduction of 10 mmHg in mPAP, to
reach an absolute value of mPAP 40 mmHg, with increased
or unchanged cardiac output [2]. Responders might benefit
from calcium channel blocker therapies rather than other
pulmonary vasodilators. In a large study, a positive vasoreac-
tivity test was observed in 12.6% of IPAH patients.
Approximately half of these were long-term responders to
CCB (6.8% of total IPAH patients) and had a significantly better
prognosis than non-responders [4]. A long-term response to
CCB was also demonstrated for some patients with DPAH [5].
Despite some positive acute vasoreactivity testing, long-term
response to CCB is virtually never observed for CTD-PAH, HIV-

PAH, PoPH, and PVOD/PCH [5]. Therefore, vasoreactivity test-

For the large majority of PAH patients, pulmonary vasoreac-
tivity testing is negative, CCB are not useful and pulmonary
vasodilator therapies should be tried. Imbalance between vaso-
constrictors (thromboxane, endothelin) and vasodilators (nitric
oxide, prostacyclin (PGI
2
)) is one of the various and complex
physiopathological mechanism that leads to the development
of PAH. Pulmonary vasodilators target three different path-
ways: 1) NO, 2) endothelin and 3) PGI
2
[6]. NO is a pulmonary
vasodilator that can be increased with phosphodiesterase-5
(PDE-5) inhibitors (sildenafil, tadalafil, and verdenafil) or guany-
late cyclase stimulators (GCs) (riociguat). Endothelin is
a pulmonary vasoconstrictor with mitogenic effects. Endothelin
antagonists (bosentan, ambrisentan, macitentan) inhibit endo-
genous endothelins effects resulting in pulmonary vasodilata-
tion. PGI
2
have vasodilator, antiplatelet, and antiproliferative
properties [7]. Synthetic PGI
2
(Intravenous (IV) epoprostenol),
PGI
2
analogs (beraprost, iloprost, treprostinil), and PGI
2
receptor
agonist (selexipag) mimic the action of endogenous PGI
2
.
2. The PGI
2
pathway: IV epoprostenol and PGI
2
analogs
Cyclooxygenase metabolizes arachidonic acid (AA) into PGI
2
,
Prostaglandin D
2
, prostaglandin E
2
, prostaglandin G
2a
, and
thromboxane, regrouped under the term prostanoids [7].
Prostanoids act via their receptors including prostaglandin
D receptor, prostaglandin E receptor (14), prostaglandin
F receptor, and PGI
2
receptor (IP receptor). Vascular endothe-
lial cells are the main producers of PGI
2,
which act mainly via
the IP receptor leading to vasodilatation, antiplatelet and
antiproliferative actions [7]. Reductions of PGI
2
urinary meta-
bolites and of PGI
2
synthase expression in the pulmonary
arteries have been shown in PAH patients [8]. Nonspecific
binding of PGI
2
to prostaglandin receptors in the gastric
mucosa has been described and could explain some side
effects [9].
We will now briefly describe the different molecules target-
ing the PGI
2
pathway in order to understand the context in
which selexipag was developed.
2.1. IV epoprostenol
IV epoprostenol is a synthetic PGI
2
. It was the first treatment
that demonstrated 6-min walk distance (6MWD) and hemody-
namic improvement in PAH patients [3,10] and it is the only
treatment that showed direct reduction of mortality in a single
randomized trial [10]. Its effect was confirmed in specific PAH
populations including CTD-PAH [11]. However IV epoprostenol
has a short half-life (35 minutes) and was initially stable at
room temperature for only 8 hours [1]. Thermostable formula-
tions now exist, avoiding the necessity of cooling, but still
require a continuous administration with a pump device in
a tunneled catheter [1]. Tachyphylaxis necessitating increasing
dose is frequently observed [3]. While thermostable formula-
tions are less cumbersome, IV epoprostenol treatment is still
inconvenient, painful, and has potential severe complications
and implications including infection, catheter obstruction,
thrombotic events, and the need for an anticoagulant therapy
[1,10]. In addition, a rebound effect can be observed when IV
epoprostenol is abruptly stopped, leading to clinical worsen-
ing and even death [1,10]. This can be observed in case of
dysfunction of the drug delivery system [10].
PGI
2
analogs (beraprost, iloprost, and treprostinil) have
been developed in order to overcome the drawbacks of IV
epoprostenol. These offered new ways of administration (sub-
cutaneous (SC), inhaled or oral) and thermostable compounds
with longer half-lives. Two oral compounds (beraprost and
treprostinil) were tested before selexipag.
2.2. Beraprost
Beraprost has been shown to improve 6MWD but had no
effect on hemodynamics [12]. In addition, it failed to show
consistent long-term clinical effect, which might be due in
part to tachyphylaxis [13,14]. Furthermore, beraprost needs
multiple administrations throughout the day (four) due to
very short half-life (1 H). Beraprost has only been used in
Asia and has never been authorized in Europe or America.
2.3. Treprostinil
Oral treprostinil was associated with an increase in 6MWD but
had no effect on the time to clinical worsening (TTCW) when
administered to PAH patients without background therapy in
one RCT (FREEDOM-M) [15]. Two RCT (FREEDOM-C and
FREEDOM-C2) tested oral treprostinil on patients with back-
ground therapy with an ERA or a PDE5-I and failed to show
improvement in 6MWD or other endpoints [16,17]. Oral
Article highlights
Pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH) is a rare pulmonary vasculo-
pathy progressively leading to right heart failure and eventually
death.
The vast majority of patients are not eligible for calcium channel
blockers therapy, because of negative acute vasoreactivity testing.
They benefit from specific pulmonary vasodilators.
Selexipag is a prostacyclin receptor agonist that has different phar-
macokinetic and pharmacodynamic properties than synthetic prosta-
cyclin (epoprostenol) and prostacyclin analogs (beraprost, iloprost,
and treprostinil)
Selexipag was demonstrated to be effective in improving
a composite outcome of morbidity-mortality in adults PAH patients
(mainly idiopathic, associated with connective tissue disease and
secondary to corrected congenital heart defects) in WHO-FC II and
III as a monotherapy, or as a sequential therapy in addition to an
endothelin receptor agonist or a phosphodiesterase 5 inhibitor.
In clinical practice, selexipag is mainly used when patients show
insufficient response to an initial oral combination therapy of an
endothelin receptor agonist and a phosphodiesterase 5 inhibitor.
Selexipag is not equivalent to parenteral prostacyclin and is not
intended to replace its use in high-risk patients.
Due to sparse data for pediatric patients, selexipag can be used on
a case-by-case basis with prudent selection and close monitoring as
we wait for the results of an ongoing randomized controlled trial
assessing the dose and efficacy of selexipag in children.

treprostinil was administered at a dose of 1 mg bid in
FREEDOM-C and FREEDOM-M. This dosage had major side
effects leading to important drop out in the treatment group
(14.4% for FREEDOM-C and 9.9% for FREEDOM M). This led to
a change of protocol in FREEDOM-M with modified intention
to treat analysis for patients starting at a dose of 0.25 mg bid
and a new study (FREEDOM-C2) that started at a dose of
0.25 mg bid [15,17]. Even though this modification of dose
reduced the dropout, the study failed to show an improve-
ment of the primary outcome (6MWD). The last RCT
(FREEDOM-EV) tested oral treprostinil in addition to
a background monotherapy (ERA or PDE-5I or GCs) [18]. Oral
treprostinil was started at a dose of 0.125 mg tid and upti-
trated to a maximum dose of 12 mg tid. It showed a reduction
in the TTCW (hazard ratio 0.75). However the adverse effects
led to discontinuation of treatment in 18.8% of patients in the
treprostinil arm against 4.1% of patients in the placebo arm. In
summary, oral treprostinil showed inconsistent clinical effect
and an unfavorable side effect profile. Oral Treprostinil has
only been used in North America and has never been author-
ized in Europe.
Administration of continuous SC treprostinil as
a monotherapy improved 6MWD, hemodynamics, and symp-
toms in one RCT [19]. The severe side effects reported with IV
epoprostenol including sepsis, venous thrombosis, and
rebound PAH were not observed with SC treprostinil [19].
However, its use is mainly limited by infusion site pain (85%
of patients) leading to premature discontinuation in 8% of
patients and limiting dose increase in a proportion of patients
[19]. This is a concern as higher doses apparently have more
effects (>13.8ng/Kg/min) [19].
Only one blinded RCT evaluated IV treprostinil efficacy and
was stopped because of safety and ethical concerns [20].
Although this trial was stopped prematurely, a significant
improvement in 6MWD, NYHA class, and Borg dyspnea scale
was observed on the treprostinil group [20]. In addition, non-
controlled trials suggesting treprostinils efficacy have been
published and transition from IV epoprostenol to IV treprostinil
has been made with mild hemodynamic worsening but WHO
functional class (WHO-FC) stability [21,22]. Initial concerns
regarding higher rate of bloodstream infections with IV trepros-
tinil use have been addressed by a change of the administration
system and diluent [23]. IV Treprostinil can be administered
through a central line via an external or implanted pump [24].
This offers several advantages over IV epoprostenol. Firstly,
thermostability is better and half-life is longer, which allows
a refill of the pump only once per month (instead of every
24 hours for IV epoprostenol). Secondly, implanted pump
allows bathing and probably reduces the occurrence of device
infection. However, it should be noted that the implantable
pump system for IV treprostinil is not yet approved and some
concerns related to the medium to long-term use of implanta-
ble pumps were recently reported [25]. IV treprostinil is classi-
cally reserved for patients intolerant to SC treprostinil [23].
Treprostinil can also be administered by inhalation. This
was evaluated in one RCT with inhaled treprostinil adminis-
tered four-time daily added to bosentan or sildenafil in NYHA
III PAH patients. This trial showed an increase in 6MWD but no
effect on TTCW or NYHA class [26]. In addition to classical side
effect of PGI
2
, increased incidence of coughing was observed
with inhaled treprostinil [26].
2.4. Iloprost
Inhaled Iloprost showed improvement in 6MWD and dyspnea,
PVR, and TTCW in WHO-FC III or IV PAH patients with no back-
ground therapy [27]. In the STEP study, inhaled iloprost added to
bosentan almost reached statistical significance for 6MWD
improvement (+26 m p = 0.051) but showed statistically signifi-
cant improvement in WHO-FC and delayed TTCW [28]. A last trial
evaluating inhaled iloprost added to bosentan was terminated
for futility [29]. The authors hypothesized that the lack of effect
was due to more severe patients than in the STEP study [29]. An
increased incidence of cough and an increased severity of syn-
cope were reported with inhaled iloprost, on top of the same
side effect profile as other PGI
2
[27,28]. The main limitations of
inhaled iloprost are the frequency of the treatment (6 to 9 times
per day) due to its very short half-life and the mandatory active
participation of the patient for a proper use of the inhalation
device. To this aim, a specific therapeutic education is required.
Oral and I.V. Iloprost exist but have never been tested in
RCT in PAH.
2.5. Summary
In summary, oral PGI
2
analogs did not show consistent clinical
efficacy and inhaled PGI
2
analogs failed to reproduce the same
clinical efficacy as parenteral therapies with the necessity of
frequent administrations (iloprost six to nine inhalations
per day, treprostinil four inhalations per day). In this context,
these treatments are far less administered than other easy to
use oral treatments targeting other pathways (ERA, PDE-5I).
Table 1 summarizes the main RCT studying the PGI
2
path-
way analyzed with the PICO (Patients, Intervention,
Comparison, Outcomes) method and adding the presence or
absence of a background therapy in addition to providing the
main results [3,1013,1519,2630].
A new easy-to-use oral treatment, with significant clinical
effect and a good safety profile targeting the PGI
2
pathway
was needed in order to improve PAH patients care. Selexipag
was tested trying to meet these goals.
3. Structure, mechanisms of action,
pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics of
selexipag
3.1. Selexipag manufacture
A molecule (BMY-42,393) having agonist activity on the IP
receptor but lacking the typical PGI
2
structure was described
for the first time in 2007 [31]. BMY-42,393 was modified to
optimize metabolic stability and agonist potency. This led to
compound 12b (MRE 269 or ACT-333,679), which had potent
and highly selective IP receptor agonist activity, and com-
pound 26a (ACT-293,987 or NS-304), the orally administered
prodrug of compound 12b, commonly called selexipag [32].
Compound 12b and 26a have diphenylpyrazine structural core
and are chemically distinct from synthetic PGI
2
or PGI
2
EXPERT REVIEW OF RESPIRATORY MEDICINE 585
analogs, therefore carrying different pharmacokinetic and
pharmacodynamic properties [32].
3.2. Mechanism of action and pharmacodynamics
ACT-333,679 is a highly selective and potent IP receptor
agonist. In rat models, it showed systemic vasodilatation
without affecting hemodynamics (e.g. no systemic hypoten-
sion) [7]. In monocrotaline PH rat model, selexipag
improved vascular endothelial dysfunction, pulmonary arter-
ial wall hypertrophy, and right ventricular hypertrophy [14].
Selexipag also caused vasodilatation of both large and small
pulmonary arteries whereas beraprost and iloprost effect
was less evident in small pulmonary arteries [14]. This
could be explained by the high selectivity of selexipag for
the IP receptor, whereas beraprost and iloprost also activate
other prostanoid receptors, including EP3 receptor and EP1
receptor leading to small pulmonary vessel vasoconstriction,
potentially attenuating the vasodilatory effect through the
IP receptor [14]. EP3 receptor and EP1 receptor activation
also lead to contraction of the gastric mucosa of rats, which
could explain a part of the gastrointestinal side effects
observed for these drugs [9]. Multiple administration of
selexipag showed a constant effect over time without tachy-
phylaxis in animal studies [7,14,30], and this was confirmed
in humans over the duration of the GRIPHON trial [30]. This
is contrary to the classical IP receptors desensitization
observed with repeated or prolonged PGI
2
or PGI
2
analogs
exposure, requiring dose increase over time (e.g. epopros-
tenol and beraprost) [3,13]. One suspected mechanism of IP
receptor desensitization is IP receptor internalization driven
through beta-Arrestin recruitment [33]. Selexipag showed
in vitro low beta-Arrestin recruitment compared to trepros-
tinil, iloprost, and beraprost [33].

3.3. Pharmacokinetics
Selexipag is administered orally with a bioavailability of
approximately 50% [34]. Once absorbed through the gastro-
intestinal tract, hydroxylation into ACT-333,679 (MRE-269)
occurs in the liver [35]. In healthy volunteers, steady-state
level of selexipag and ACT-333,679 are reached within 3 days
of oral administration, and ACT-333,679 concentration is three
to fourfold higher than selexipag level [36]. The starting dose
is 200 g twice daily, with weekly uptitration of 200 g twice
daily to the highest tolerated dose or 1600 g twice daily,
which was the maximum tolerated dose in healthy volun-
teers [36].
In healthy male volunteers, the maximum plasma concen-
trations of selexipag and ACT-333,679 after the administration
of 200 g of selexipag were reached after 2.5 and 4 hours
respectively [35]. Mean half-lives were 0.72.3 hours for selex-
ipag and 9.414.22 hours for ACT-333,679 [35]. In clinical
practice, this allows for a twice-daily administration. Despite
better oral absorption of selexipag when given fasted, selex-
ipag intake is recommended with food, in order to improve
tolerability [35].
Hydroxylation of selexipag to its active metabolite ACT-
333,679 is catalyzed in liver microsomes mainly by carboxyles-
terase 1, and to a small percentage by carboxylesterase 2
[37,38]. A small part of the hydroxylation of selexipag into
ACT-333,679 might already take place in the intestine through
human intestinal microsomes catalyzed by carboxylesterase 2
[38]. Cytochrome P450 (CYP) 3A4 and CYP2C8 also metabolize
selexipag with oxidation and dealkylation reactions [37]. ACT-
333,679 undergoes glucuronidation by UDP-
glucuronosyltransferase (UGT) 1A3 and UGT2B7 [37]. As for
selexipag, ACT 333,679 is also metabolized by CYP3A4 and
CYP2C8 [37]. The excretion of selexipag, ACT-333,679 and their
metabolic products are mostly biliary (approximately 90%)
[39]. In vitro, selexipag and ACT-333,679 are weak substrates
of OATP1B1 and OATP1B3 and selexipag is a weak substrate of
the efflux pump P-Gp [40].
3.4. Renal insufficiency and hepatic impairment
Severe renal insufficiency (GFR 1530 ml/min/m
2
) as well as
mild and moderate hepatic impairment (Child-Pugh A and B)
increased selexipag and ACT-333,679 exposure [39]. In this
study, no safety concerns were raised without dose adjust-
ment [39]. However, a careful uptitration of selexipag in these
settings seems wise. The number of patients with severe
hepatic impairment (Child Pugh C) was too small to draw
any conclusion. To our opinion selexipag should be withheld
in this population.
3.5. Drug-to-selexipag interactions
As shown in an open-label, randomized, crossover design
study with healthy volunteers, strong CYP2C8 inhibitors (like
gemfibrozil) increase ACT-333,679 concentration and the side
effects commonly attributed to selexipag administration,
whereas strong CYP2C8 inducers (like rifampicin) diminish
exposure to ACT-333,679 [41]. Clopidogrel, another CYP2C8
inhibitor, also seemed to increase the exposition to ACT-
333,679, but with smaller effect than Gemfibrozil [42]. In line
with these studies, strong CYP2C8 should be avoided, but
some less potent CYP2C8 inhibitors (e.g. clopidogrel) could
be used with appropriate dose reduction [42]. Administration
of concomitant strong CYP2C8 inducers might require dose
increase [41]. Co-administration of CYP 3A4, OATP transpor-
ters, or P-Gp inhibitors (lopinavir and ritonavir) with selexipag
seems safe without dose adjustment [40].
3.6. Selexipag-to-drug interactions
In vitro studies have found that selexipag is a CYP2C8 and
CYP2C9 inhibitor, and a CYP3A4 and CYP2C9 inducer [37].
Selexipag also inhibits OATP1B1, OATP1B3, OAT1, OAT3, and
BCRP transporters [37]. However, the risk of causing selexipag-
to-drug interactions is low because the concentration needed
to create an effect in vitro is higher than the plasma level
expected in vivo with the current dose recommendations [37].
This is supported by in vivo data demonstrating no change of
exposure observed with co-administration of selexipag with
S-warfarine (CYP2C9 substrate), R-Warfarine (CYP3A4 sub-
strate), or midazolam (CYP3A4 hepatic and intestinal sub-
strate) [43,44].
4. Phase II trial of selexipag
Selexipag first showed significant hemodynamic effect with
acceptable safety profile in 43 PAH adults in a phase II proof
of concept study published in 2012 [45]. The randomization
was 3:1 (selexipag: placebo). Selexipag was started at 200 g
twice daily and titrated with 200 g increments up to the
maximum dosage of 800 g twice daily. Per-protocol analysis
showed a 30.3% reduction of PVR after 17 weeks of treatment
with selexipag compared to placebo. Robustness of results
was confirmed with all-treated set analysis. This encouraged
the GRIPHON trial published in 2015 [30].
5. GRIPHON trial
The GRIPHON trial is a multicentre, event-driven, phase 3,
double-blind RCT, that included 1156 adult PAH patients ran-
domized to receive selexipag titrated to maximal individual
tolerated dosage (maximum dose 1600 g twice daily) or
placebo. Recruited patients could either be treatment nave
or already take a background therapy (ERA and/or PDE5-I). The
primary outcome was a composite of death from any cause or
a complication related to PAH (i.e. disease progression, wor-
sening of PAH that resulted in hospitalization, initiation of
parenteral PGI
2
therapy, the need for long-term oxygen ther-
apy, lung transplantation, or balloon atrial septostomy). The
trial lasted up to the end of the treatment period (defined as
7 days after the date of the last intake of selexipag or placebo),
and median follow-up was 63.7 and 70.7 weeks in the placebo
and selexipag arms respectively. The risk of meeting the pri-
mary composite endpoint was significantly lower with selex-
ipag than with placebo (hazard ratio of 0.60 with 99%
confidence interval of 0.46 to 0.78 (p < 0.05). This effect was
mainly driven by less disease progression and hospitalization
EXPERT REVIEW OF RESPIRATORY MEDICINE 587
(81.9% of the events) whereas no significant effect was seen
on mortality [30].

6. Expert opinion
6.1. Is selexipag more effective than ERA, PDE-5I or GCs?
The primary outcome of PAH trials has progressively switched
from 6MWD to TTCW. This change occurred for different rea-
sons. The main one is probably that 6MWD inconsistently
correlated with long-term outcomes, including death [46].
Furthermore, an increase in 6MWD seemed more difficult to
demonstrate, as included patients were less symptomatic, with
improvement of PAH treatments and presence of background
therapies [47]. TTCW was suggested because it seemed to be
able to capture a significant therapeutic effect with possible
better correlation with long-term outcomes. Indeed, morbidity
as defined in SERAPHIN and GRIPHON trials was strongly
associated with mortality at 3, 6, and 12 months [48].
However, TTCW is still not the perfect surrogate marker.
Firstly, it is a composite outcome with different components
not weighted for their relative importance (e.g. mortality and
hospitalization), and secondly, its definition varies between
different PAH studies.
The change of primary outcome added to the growing
inclusion of patients with background therapies, and the
absence of head-to-head comparison of different PAH thera-
pies make comparisons of efficacy of the different pulmonary
vasodilators difficult. In this context, it is impossible to say if
selexipag is more or less effective than an ERA, a PDE-5I, or
a GCs.
6.2. Is Selexipag more effective than its concurrent oral
treatments targeting the PGI2 pathway?
Beraprost failed to show long-term (9 and 12 months) clinical
effect, possibly due to tachyphylaxis, while the effect of selex-
ipag persisted without an evidence for attenuation, even
though the time analysis of GRIPHON was long (70.7 weeks
in median for the selexipag arm) [13,14,30]. Oral treprostinil
showed inconsistent clinical effect when used as a sequential
therapy (added on an ERA or PDE5-I) with a poor tolerability
[1618]. Selexipag was effective in reducing TTCW including in
patients already on background therapy [30]. Based on this,
selexipag seems more effective than these two molecules
while keeping a good safety profile.
6.3. Is there still a role for inhaled treprostinil or
iloprost?
Inhaled treatments both have specific minor side effects (e.g.
coughing) and some more severe (severity of syncope for
iloprost) side effects. Furthermore, they require multiples
administrations throughout the day (four times for treprostinil,
six to nine times for iloprost), making patients adherence
challenging. These inhaled treatments do not seem to be
more effective than selexipag, even though a direct
comparison is impossible. However, due to the abovemen-
tioned drawbacks, selexipag seems more convenient. The
TRANSIT-1 trial evaluated the switch from inhaled treprostinil
to selexipag on 34 WHO-FC II or III PAH patients with
a transition lasting 12 weeks [49]. The transition was successful
and well-tolerated in most patients, with 82.4% of patients
successfully switched, and 3 patients discontinuing selexipag
due to adverse events [49].
6.4. Is selexipag equivalent to parenteral PGI
2
?
The GRIPHON study mainly included patients in WHO-FC II
(529 patients, 45.8% of the total population) and III (607
patients, 52.5% of the total population). Virtually no patients
were in WHO-FC I or IV [30]. This is probably due to the
inclusion criteria of a 6MWD between 50 m and 450 m, and
the reticence to include WHO-FC IV patients in the modern
treatment era, with the widely accepted strategy of an early
aggressive therapy including parenteral PGI
2
in the most
severe cases.
In a post-hoc analysis, selexipag was associated with
a reduction in TTCW independent of the initial risk profile
(low, moderate, or high) evaluated by the REVEAL 2.0 risk
method assessment and the noninvasive French assessment
[46]. Interestingly, treatment effect was more pronounced in
the low and intermediate risk categories than in the high-risk
profile [46]. Moreover, risk subgroup was prognostic for the
outcome, regardless of the timing of assessment. This study
has two major implications. Firstly, it underscores the impor-
tance of aiming for a low-risk profile, and suggests that even
low-risk profile patients may benefit from treatment escala-
tion. Secondly, the reduced treatment effect of selexipag
noted in high-risk profile patients emphasizes the need for
rapid escalation of treatments with triple therapy including
parenteral PGI
2
in these patients with a poor prognosis. No
time should be lost on trying selexipag.
In Europe, there are mainly three choices of parenteral PGI
2
:
IV Epoprostenol, IV treprostinil, and SC treprostinil.
IV Epoprostenol remains the only treatment that showed
a significant effect on mortality in a single RCT published in
1996, including mainly PAH patients in WHO-FC III and IV [50].
It is the only treatment with a class I level A recommendation
for patient in WHO-FC IV. The French PAH team described
eight cases of PAH patients transitioned from IV epoprostenol
to selexipag, due to refusal to continue parenteral treatment
or because of recurrent catheter-related infections [51]. Even
though transition was well tolerated in all cases, risk profile
worsened during follow-up, especially due to worsening
hemodynamic data (and particularly reduction of cardiac out-
put) [51]. This adds to the knowledge that selexipag is not
equivalent to IV epoprostenol and should not replace it. In our
opinion, IV Epoprostenol remains the optimal drug for an
aggressive therapy for patients presenting with a high-risk
profile on initial evaluation or for patients with progression
despite initial oral therapies. For high-risk and young patients
on initial evaluation we like to start aggressively with upfront
triple therapy including an ERA, a PDE5-I, and IV epoprostenol
as this combination was shown to be effective on small num-
ber of patients and is logically attractable [52].
588 L. GENECAND ET AL.
SC treprostinil is an attractive parenteral option because
it avoids the severe side effects associated with IV epopros-
tenol with clear clinical efficacy. Even though IV treprostinil
is not recommended in the current guidelines, it is used in
clinical practice because of its advantages over IV epopros-
tenol including refill of the device once per month and an
implanted pump that allows bathing. A transition from
treprostinil (3 IV, 1 SC) to selexipag was studied in 4 PAH
patients. While transitioning seemed safe, they did not eval-
uate hemodynamics by RHC after the transition and a full
evaluation of the risk profile was lacking [53]. Another study
of five WHO-FC I PAH patients transitioning from treprostinil
(4 IV, 1 SC) to selexipag showed safe transitioning but
a trend toward worsening hemodynamics including cardiac
output without long-term data after the transition [54].
In conclusion, selexipag is not intended to replace parent-
eral PGI
2
in high-risk patients. We dont support a transition
from parenteral PGI
2
to selexipag, except in rare cases of
impossibility to continue parenteral PGI
2
because of side
effects or due to practical reasons as most data show hemo-
dynamics and/or risk profile worsening with sufficient follow-
up time after transition. A transition could be considered in
highly selected cases that have normalized their hemody-
namics (mPAP, PVR) and with a close follow up after
transition.
6.5. Is selexipag validated for all etiology of PAH?
Table 2 shows the detailed population of the published PAH
RCT targeting the PGI
2
and the endothelin pathways [3,10
13,1519,2630,47,5561]. RCT targeting the NO pathway are
not shown for clarity but they globally have a similar popula-
tion repartition. The main population included is IPAH and
CTD-PAH. There are few data for HPAH, DPAH, HIV-PAH, CHD-
PAH, and PoPH (21 patients in the ALPHABET trial and 85
patients in PORTICO trial) [12,61]. No patients with schistoso-
miasis induced PAH were studied in RCT. For the underrepre-
sented populations, current guidelines suggest to follow the
same PAH treatment algorithm in addition to addressing the
underlying cause (HAART for HIV, specific treatment of portal
hypertension for PoPH, specific treatment of schistosomia-
sis) [1].
The GRIPHON trials population was no different than
other trial in the field of PAH. It included IPAH (n = 649),
HPAH (n = 26), DPAH (n = 27), CTD-PAH (n = 334), CHD-
PAH with corrected congenital heart defects (n = 110), and
HIV-related PAH (n = 10). Post-hoc analysis on CTD-PAH
showed significant delay of TTCW with hazard ratio of 0.59
95% CI (0.410.89), which was consistent over CTD subtype
(especially systemic scleroderma and systemic lupus
erythematous) and the presence or not of a background
therapy [62]. One other post-hoc analysis looked at the 110
PAH patients with corrected congenital heart defects (55
atrial septal defects, 38 ventricular septal defect, 14 persis-
tent ductus arteriosus, 3 not specified) and showed a non-
statistically significant trend toward a reduced risk of the
primary composite endpoint (hazard ratio 0.58, 95% IC
0.251.37) that can probably be attributed to the lack of
power [63].
Selexipag is validated for IPAH and CTD-PAH. Small but
informative numbers of patients with HPAH, DPAH, and cor-
rected congenital shunts were included in the study and the
use of selexipag seemed safe and effective in these popula-
tions. For other types of PAH (HIV, PoPH, schistosomiasis, CHD
other than corrected congenital heart defect), no formal con-
clusions can be drawn but it seems reasonable to use it as we
use all other PAH therapies without studies addressing speci-
fically these populations.

6.6. Is Selexipag validated for monotherapy or as
a combination therapy?
In the GRIPHON study 236 patients had no background ther-
apy, 170 had an ERA, 374 had a PDE-5I and 376 had
a combination of PDE5-I + ERA. At baseline, more than 70%
of the patients were receiving one or more PAH drugs and
30% were treated with dual combination therapy. The effect
of selexipag on TTCW was similar whether it was started as
a monotherapy or added to a mono or a bi-therapy [30]. On
a post-hoc analysis, when Selexipag was added to
a combination therapy (ERA + PDE-5I), the magnitude of effect
on the TTCW was similar as when it was started as
a monotherapy and this was also true when analyzing sepa-
rately patients in WHO-FC II or III [64]. In line with these results,
selexipag is indicated as sequential therapy on an ERA or
a PDE-5I in WHO FC-II and WHO FC-III patients with a class
I Level B of recommendation [1]. The same class and level of
recommendation are attributed to selexipag as
a monotherapy in the current guidelines [1].
As shown in the AMBITION trial, initial combination therapy
is more effective than initial monotherapy for the treatment of
PAH [65]. Initial combination therapy with selexipag and an
ERA or a PDE-5I were never directly tested and is not sup-
ported in the most recent guidelines [1]. However it seems
reasonable to think that initial combination therapy of selex-
ipag with an ERA or selexipag with a PDE5-I is a possibility,
especially when there are contra-indications to an ERA or
a PDE-5I.
6.7. When do we use selexipag in adults?
The proceeding of the 6
th
world symposium on PH favored
initial oral combination therapy for the majority of newly
diagnosed PAH patients with only a residual role for initial
monotherapy including very mild disease or special etiologies
(mild HIV-PAH, mild PoPH, uncorrected CHF, PAH with overt
feature of venous involvement) [50]. Risk profile assessment
remains a critical step to determine the appropriate therapy
(initial combination therapy, monotherapy, or an initial com-
bination therapy including a parenteral PGI
2
).
Most patients that are newly diagnosed with PAH fall into
the intermediate-risk profile category and are typically started
on an initial oral double combination therapy. The
combination with the most solid level of recommendation is
ambrisentan (ERA) and tadalafil (PDE-5I), as reported in the
AMBITION trial [65]. In line with the evidence, we favor this
combination or at least a combination of an ERA and a PDE-5I.
Follow-up evaluation with risk assessment is made after
3 months of therapy. In case of improvement to low-risk
profile, we consider further follow up without adding
a molecule. In case of stagnation to an intermediate-risk pro-
file, we add selexipag (triple oral combination therapy) and in
case of deterioration to a high-risk profile, we add a parenteral
PGI
2
, usually IV Epoprostenol. An initial oral double combina-
tion therapy with selexipag added to an ERA or a PDE-5I has
never been studied in an RCT. Furthermore, this combination
would be harder to manage at three months when the risk
assessment evaluation is made. Indeed, if a patient is evalu-
ated high-risk profile at three months, there would be
a temptation to add a third molecule (either ERA or PDE-5I
based on the initial combination) in addition to switching
selexipag to a parenteral PGI
2
therapy. In light of these reflex-
ions, we never use selexipag as part of the initial double
combination therapy except in the presence of clear contra-
indication to an ERA or a PDE-5I.
An RCT explored the efficacy and safety of initial triple
(selexipag, macitentan, tadalafil) versus initial dual (maciten-
tan, tadalafil, placebo) oral combination therapy in 247
patients with newly diagnosed PAH (TRITON, NCT02558231).
The results of the TRITON trial were recently presented and
demonstrated no benefit on PVR (primary outcome) with
a statistically non-significant trend for improved long-term
outcome with initial triple versus initial double therapy [66].
An expert panel suggested detailed recommendations for
the use of selexipag based on clinical scenarios [67]. This
expert consensus is an easy-to-use guide to help clinicians to
know if a patient has an indication (expert point of view) for
selexipag and is in line with what we usually do in our practice
when we add selexipag for an intermediate-risk patient at the
three months follow up.
6.8. When do we use selexipag in pediatric patients?
The first reported use of selexipag in a child was in 2017, two
years after the publication of the adult GRIPHON trial [30,68].
This case report showed improvement in hemodynamics and
WHO-FC after addition of selexipag to an initial dual combina-
tion of ERA and PDE-5I in a 12 years old girl with HPAH after
a follow-up of 6 months [68]. In a recent observational study,
15 children with PH from different etiologies (8 IPAH, 1 HPAH,
3 PAH-CHD, 2 PH group 3 and 1 PH group 5) were started on
selexipag in addition to a dual therapy of an ERA and a PDE-5I
[69]. After a minimum of 6 months follow-up, selexipag
seemed safe, and improved outcome relevant variables in
half of the children. Of note, efficacy seemed to be better in
less severe patients [69]. Another report in three children (1 PH
group 3, 2 IPAH) showed clinical stabilization when selexipag
was used in association with a PDE-5I and/or an ERA [70].
A transition from SC treprostinil to selexipag was successful
in one child with IPAH from the same study with no clinical
worsening but slight elevation of BNP after 24 months [70]. In
one other observational study, selexipag was added on top of

selexipag have been elaborated with similar pharmacokinetic
characteristics [73].
7. Post-marketing surveillance
The side effects of Selexipag summarized from the GRIPHON
trial are shown in Table 3 and are consistent with PGI
2
therapies (headache, gastro-intestinal side effects (diarrhea,
nausea, vomiting), pain in jaw and in extremities, myalgia,
and flushing) [30]. Regarding post-safety analysis, one case
report of Rosacea possibly attributed to selexipag was pub-
lished [74]. A study comparing selexipag and moxifloxacin
showed that Selexipag does not have an effect on cardiac
repolarization (QTc duration) [75].
Abrupt discontinuation of parenteral PGI
2
and especially
IV Epoprostenol can cause rebound effect associated with
clinical deterioration even leading to death. A substudy
from the GRIPHON trial showed that treatment was inter-
rupted at least 1 time in 19.3% of patients of the selexipag
group and 10% of patients of the placebo group [76]. The
main reason for interruptions was adverse events. No
rebound effect was described with selexipag interrup-
tion [76].
Five patients receiving selexipag died during post-
marketing surveillance. This raised concerns and a review of
the European Medicine Agency concluded that selexipag was
not linked to increased mortality and concluded that selexipag
could continue to be used and prescribed according to cur-
rent prescribing information [77].

9. Five year perspectives
Quite disappointingly, the last five years have seen no valida-
tion of a new drug in PAH. Indeed, the three well-known PAH
pathophysiological pathways have now been thoroughly tar-
geted and selexipag validation filled the last remaining gap of
an effective oral molecule targeting the PGI
2
pathway. The
treatment strategy has been reevaluated, with a change
toward more aggressive approaches (upfront initial combina-
tion with rapid escalation). To our opinion, research in the next
five years must now focus on new promising treatments. This
is not without difficulties in a rare disease like PAH, but many
efforts to find new drugs targeting other mechanisms, includ-
ing inflammation, metabolism dysfunction, cell therapy,
genetically determined targets, pulmonary denervation, and
other mechanisms are underway and are summarized else-
where [46].

10. Conclusions
Selexipag is a PGI
2
receptor agonist that is effective in PAH
WHO-FC II and III, either as a monotherapy, or as a sequential
therapy on an ERA or a PDE-5I or as a combination of the two
(triple combination therapy). Most patients with newly diag-
nosed PAH fall into the intermediate-risk category. According
to the current guidelines, these patients benefit from an initial
combination therapy with an ERA or a PDE-5I. If the patient is
still at intermediate risk after 3 months of this regimen we
typically add selexipag for an oral triple combination therapy.
If a contra-indication for an ERA or a PDE-5I exists, selexipag
could be considered as part of the initial upfront oral combi-
nation therapy. Selexipag should not replace parenteral PGI
2
for high-risk patients. However, when parenteral PGI
2
cannot
be continued, due to side effects or patients choice, transition
to Selexipag could be considered in highly selected cases
despite very scarce data concerning this strategy. This option
should however not delay further therapeutic options, includ-
ing lung transplantation or balloon atrial septostomy.
